1
00:00:00,709 --> 00:00:01,918
The prison was upstairs

2
00:00:03,125 --> 00:00:04,667
When they took me upstairs

3
00:00:05,709 --> 00:00:07,709
He whipped me a few lashes the first time

4
00:00:09,042 --> 00:00:11,500
My eyes were blindfolded and shut

5
00:00:12,292 --> 00:00:14,209
And they brought me to the prison door

6
00:00:14,584 --> 00:00:17,125
He opened the door, uncovered my eyes, then pushed me inside

7
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:21,959
When he gave me those first lashes, I entered the prison

8
00:00:23,334 --> 00:00:24,876
I told myself, I’m going to die, may God have mercy on me

9
00:00:27,959 --> 00:00:32,083
You don’t know whether he’ll let you out or not

10
00:00:32,709 --> 00:00:35,876
You don’t know if he’ll send you home or to Wadi Okab

11
00:00:39,250 --> 00:00:41,959
Interviewer: What’s Wadi Okab? Witness: It’s our graveyard

12
00:00:49,375 --> 00:00:55,125
Interviewer: How long did you spend in the cell you were in?

13
00:00:55,375 --> 00:00:57,500
And how did you feel being detained there?

14
00:01:00,792 --> 00:01:03,834
The feeling was anxiety and fear

15
00:01:05,042 --> 00:01:08,751
I was detained with them for six days the first time

16
00:01:10,542 --> 00:01:14,459
But the anxiety, fear, and overthinking

17
00:01:15,667 --> 00:01:21,125
Because of that you can’t focus, and you lose your appetite

18
00:01:22,042 --> 00:01:23,667
And you don’t even want to drink water

19
00:01:24,667 --> 00:01:27,959
We lost our nerves because we had no cigarettes for six days

20
00:01:28,459 --> 00:01:29,667
As you know, I’m a smoker

21
00:01:30,834 --> 00:01:33,876
And I’ve been smoking cigarettes for a long time

22
00:01:34,417 --> 00:01:39,292
I’m the type who can’t stay away from a cigarette for more than an hour

23
00:01:40,918 --> 00:01:43,709
So when I stayed six days without cigarettes, I lost my nerves

24
00:01:44,584 --> 00:01:46,834
And I say thank God I didn’t lose my mind

25
00:01:48,167 --> 00:01:52,042
Whether from torture, not smoking, or from the stress

26
00:01:59,334 --> 00:02:03,417
Interviewer: How did you spend your time inside the room?

27
00:02:05,542 --> 00:02:11,250
I spent most of my time asking forgiveness and in <i>duaa</i> [prayer]

28
00:02:11,876 --> 00:02:17,209
I spent my time praying to God to deliver me from them

29
00:02:22,626 --> 00:02:25,876
Interviewer: Did they stop you from talking inside the rooms?

30
00:02:25,918 --> 00:02:28,250
And were you detained alone in that room?

31
00:02:28,250 --> 00:02:29,626
Or how many were with you?

32
00:02:29,667 --> 00:02:33,709
No, there were prisoners already there before me

33
00:02:34,959 --> 00:02:37,167
So when I entered, there were already prisoners inside

34
00:02:38,209 --> 00:02:39,876
Some were brought in for smuggling

35
00:02:39,876 --> 00:02:43,709
Or for doing something else, for example

36
00:02:44,250 --> 00:02:45,918
Or for smoking cigarettes

37
00:02:47,250 --> 00:02:48,751
Or for praying

38
00:02:50,918 --> 00:02:53,959
There were many prisoners, not just one or two

39
00:02:57,209 --> 00:02:59,918
Interviewer: Could you talk among yourselves?

40
00:03:00,792 --> 00:03:03,626
We used to talk quietly

41
00:03:04,709 --> 00:03:06,709
I mean, in a low voice

42
00:03:08,500 --> 00:03:11,542
Interviewer: What did you talk about? Witness: We just talked among ourselves

43
00:03:12,292 --> 00:03:13,959
Because we knew each other

44
00:03:14,667 --> 00:03:18,375
When I came in, I saw two or three I knew from my area

45
00:03:18,918 --> 00:03:20,959
So we talked in low voices

46
00:03:21,709 --> 00:03:24,042
We didn’t want anyone to hear us, because we were afraid

47
00:03:24,876 --> 00:03:26,209
Interviewer: What did you talk about?

48
00:03:26,250 --> 00:03:31,083
About what each of us had, and when they might release us

49
00:03:31,125 --> 00:03:33,667
Or whether they’d execute us, we didn’t know

50
00:03:33,834 --> 00:03:35,042
That was our talk

51
00:03:37,292 --> 00:03:41,542
And most of the talk was about worrying for our children

52
00:03:42,417 --> 00:03:43,876
Because you’re not alone

53
00:03:44,375 --> 00:03:48,083
You left behind a family, that’s the fear

54
00:03:51,250 --> 00:03:57,959
Interviewer: What sounds did you hear while you were inside the room?

55
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,459
And how did the place smell as well?

56
00:04:05,209 --> 00:04:07,459
We used to hear sounds

57
00:04:08,500 --> 00:04:09,959
They brought in people

58
00:04:11,334 --> 00:04:13,209
Their voices were loud during torture

59
00:04:13,250 --> 00:04:16,751
And during interrogation they screamed

60
00:04:16,959 --> 00:04:18,792
That was from beating or whipping

61
00:04:19,959 --> 00:04:22,083
Or from electric shocks, no one knew what it was

62
00:04:23,125 --> 00:04:25,083
No one knew what they were doing to him

63
00:04:26,250 --> 00:04:30,626
But it was clear from his voice that he was being interrogated

64
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:34,500
So they screamed, saying, By God, I didn’t do that

65
00:04:34,918 --> 00:04:39,000
And if you swore by anything other than God, they’d beat you even harder
